'''Robert Glenn Ray''' (born October 1, 1991) is an American professional [[baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He made his MLB debut in 2014 for the [[Detroit Tigers]], and was traded to the Diamondbacks before the 2015 season. Ray was an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|MLB All-Star]] in 2017.

==Career==

Ray attended [[Brentwood High School (Tennessee)|Brentwood High School]] in [[Brentwood, Tennessee]]. He committed to attend the [[University of Arkansas]].

===Washington Nationals===
[[File:Robbie Ray IMG 1203 (13316834923).jpg|upright|thumb|Ray with the [[2014 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers in 2014]] spring training]]
The [[Washington Nationals]] selected Ray in the 12th round of the [[2010 Major League Baseball draft]]. He signed with the Nationals, receiving a $799,000 [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilgore |first=Adam |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2010/08/nationals_announce_signing_of.html |title=Nationals announce signing of Robbie Ray |work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 16, 2010 |accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref>

Ray pitched in one game for the [[Vermont Lake Monsters]] in 2010, striking out two in one inning pitched. Pitching for the [[Hagerstown Suns]] in 2011, he went 2–3 with a 3.13 [[earned run average]] with 95 [[strikeouts]] in 89 [[inning]]s pitched.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sheinin |first=Dave |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/a-dazzling-debut-for-hagerstowns-robbie-ray/2011/05/10/AF5mjyhG_blog.html |title=A dazzling debut for Hagerstown's Robbie Ray |publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' |date=May 10, 2011 |accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref>

Ray struggled pitching for the [[Potomac Nationals]] in 2012, going 4–12 with a 6.56 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|last=Seiner |first=Jake |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130606&content_id=49767492&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb |title=Ray continues to rebound for Nats |publisher=''[[Minor League Baseball]]'' |date=January 2, 2013 |accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> He returned to Potomac for the start of the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilgore |first=Adam |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2013/05/02/a-j-cole-robbie-ray-together-again-at-potomac/ |title=A. J. Cole, Robbie Ray together again at Potomac |publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' |date=May 2, 2013 |accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> After going 6–3 with a 3.11 ERA and 100 strikeouts in 84 innings, he was promoted to the Double-A [[Harrisburg Senators]].<ref>{{cite journal |first= Geoff |last=Morrow |url=http://www.pennlive.com/senators/index.ssf/2013/07/robbie_ray_makes_double-a_debu.html |title=Robbie Ray makes Double-A debut for Harrisburg Senators in opener of Friday night doubleheader on City Island |newspaper=[[The Patriot News]] |date=July 5, 2013 |accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref> He posted a 5–2 record with a 3.72 ERA at Harrisburg.

===Detroit Tigers===
On December 2, 2013, Ray was traded to the [[Detroit Tigers]], along with [[Ian Krol]] and [[Steve Lombardozzi Jr.]], for [[Doug Fister]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/news/article/det/detroit-tigers-trade-doug-fister-to-washington-nationals-for-three-players?ymd=20131202&content_id=64343036&vkey=news_det |title=Tigers send Fister to Nats for three players |publisher=''[[Major League Baseball]]'' |first=Jason |last=Beck |date=December 2, 2013 |accessdate=December 3, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206034225/http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/news/article/det/detroit-tigers-trade-doug-fister-to-washington-nationals-for-three-players?ymd=20131202&content_id=64343036&vkey=news_det |archivedate=December 6, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.freep.com/article/20140216/SPORTS02/302160082/detroit-tigers-robbie-ray-doug-fister |title=He may be key to Doug Fister deal, but lefty Robbie Ray knows he must prove himself to Detroit Tigers |first=George |last=Sipple |newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]] |date=February 16, 2014 |accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref>

Ray started the [[2014 Detroit Tigers season|2014 season]] with the Triple-A [[Toledo Mud Hens]].  The Tigers announced he would be called up to the Major League team following an April 26 injury to starter [[Aníbal Sánchez]]. Ray made his Major League debut on May 6, 2014, earning his first big-league win in the Tigers' 11–4 victory over the [[Houston Astros]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gametracker/recap/MLB_20140506_HOU@DET |title=Tigers 11, Astros 4 |publisher=''[[CBS Sports]]'' |date=May 6, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> On August 12, he was recalled to replace an injured Aníbal Sánchez again. Ray pitched five innings, allowing four runs on six hits, while striking out five and walking two, in a 4–2 loss to the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.mlive.com/tigers/index.ssf/2014/08/tigers_pirates_robbie_ray.html | title = Pirates 4, Tigers 2: Robbie Ray takes loss, bats silent as Detroit losing streak reaches four games | publisher = ''[[MLive]]'' | first = Chris | last = Iott | date = August 12, 2014 | accessdate = August 12, 2014 }}</ref>

===Arizona Diamondbacks===
On December 5, 2014, the Tigers traded Ray and [[Domingo Leyba]] to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] in a three-team trade that brought [[Shane Greene]] to the Detroit Tigers, and [[Didi Gregorius]] to the [[New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://m.tigers.mlb.com/news/article/103253536/didi-gregorius-goes-to-yankees-in-three-team-trade | title = Gregorius goes to Yanks, Ray to Arizona, Greene to Tigers | publisher = ''[[Major League Baseball|MLB]]'' | first = Joey | last = Nowak | date = December 5, 2014 | accessdate = December 5, 2014 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141210171036/http://m.tigers.mlb.com/news/article/103253536/didi-gregorius-goes-to-yankees-in-three-team-trade | archivedate = December 10, 2014 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  He started the 2015 season at their AAA affiliate, the Reno Aces.<ref>http://www.kolotv.com/sports/headlines/Diamondbacks-Make-4-Roster-Moves-After-Final-Spring-Game-298688391.html</ref> He made his debut in a Diamondbacks uniform on May 6, being called up to face the [[Colorado Rockies]] in the second game of a doubleheader.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/gametracker/recap/MLB_20150506_ARI@COL_2 |title=Gregorius Diamondbacks earn 1st DH sweep on road since 2006 |publisher=cbssports.com |first=Pat |last=Graham | date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref>

Ray hit his first career home run on June 7, 2016, off of [[Chris Archer]]. Despite striking out 218 batters, Ray finished 8-15 with a 4.90 ERA in 174⅓ innings in 32 starts, giving up 24 home runs and recording just 10 quality starts in 32 total starts. In 2016 he led the major leagues in allowing opposing batters the highest [[batting average on balls in play]] (.352).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2015&month=0&season1=2015&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=12,d Major League Leaderboards » 2015 » Pitchers » Dashboard | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

In his first month and a half of 2017, Ray pitched poorly, recording a 4.57 ERA in 8 starts. In his following 8 starts, however, he went 6-1 with a 1.81 ERA in 54⅔ innings, holding opponents to a .173 batting average. He pitched his first career complete game shutout on May 30 against the Pirates, striking out 10 while allowing just four hits. In his next two starts he struck out 11 and 12 batters respectively. In a five start stretch (those three and the two prior to the shutout), Ray went 5-0 with an 0.24 ERA (1 ER in 37 innings) holding opponents to a .115 batting average (just 14 hits allowed) and 48 strikeouts. On July 2, Ray was named to his first career All-Star game. At the time, he had an 8-4 record and a 3.06 ERA in 100 innings, with a .202 batting average against and 128 strikeouts. In a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] on July 28, Ray was struck in the head on a line drive by Cardinal first baseman [[Luke Voit]] in the 2nd inning and carted off the field, but a CT scan later showed that he did not suffer any fracture and only needed a few stitches to his head.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/mlb/diamondbacks/2017/07/29/robbie-ray-diamondbacks-pitcher-hit-head/522144001/|title=Robbie Ray hit in head by line drive, knocked out of loss to Cardinals|publisher=azcentral.com|first=Nick|last=Piecoro|date=July 28, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/mlb/diamondbacks/2017/07/30/diamondbacks-lineup-dbacks-pitching-walker-cardinals/523617001/|title=Robbie Ray thankful head injury wasn't worse|publisher=azcentral.com|first=Nick|last=Piecoro|date=July 30, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> He was put on the 7-day concussion DL and did not return to the mound until August 24. On September 4, Ray struck out a career-high 14 batters while pitching 7 2/3 innings in a 13-0 victory against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]. Ray earned his 12th victory of the season, and this would propel the Diamondbacks to their 11th consecutive victory. He finished the season with 15-5 with 218 strikeouts and a 2.89 ERA over 162 innings in 28 starts. His 12.11 K/9 rate was the best in the National League and he held opponents to a .199 batting average. In 2017 he had the highest rate of [[bases on balls per 9 innings pitched]] in the majors (3.94), and led the majors in giving up the highest percentage of hard-hit balls (40.4%).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=20,d Major League Leaderboards » 2017 » Pitchers » Batted Ball Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=10,d Major League Leaderboards » 2017 » Pitchers » Dashboard | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He also led major league pitchers in lowest contact percentage (67.9%).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=5&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=8,a Major League Leaderboards » 2017 » Pitchers » Plate Discipline Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Ray began the 2018 season as the Diamondbacks #2 starter. He was placed on the disabled list on April 30 with an oblique injury.<ref>[https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/mlb/diamondbacks/2018/04/30/arizona-diamondbacks-robbie-ray-disabled-list-oblique-strain/567158002/ Arizona Diamondbacks news: Robbie Ray heads to DL with oblique strain<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He finished the season 6-2 with an ERA of 3.93 in 24 starts. In {{frac|123|2|3}} innings, he struck out 165 batters, and gave up 70 walks.

==Pitch selection==
Ray throws a [[fastball]] in the {{convert|92|-|95|mph}} range, topping out at {{convert|98|mph}}.  His primary offspeed pitches are a [[slider]] that averages about {{convert|85|mph}} (tops out at {{convert|87|mph}}) and a [[curveball]] that he throws at about {{convert|84|mph}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/pitchfx.aspx?playerid=11486&position=P |title=Robbie Ray PitchFX at FanGraphs.com |publisher=fangraphs.com| accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Ray married Taylor Pasma on November 2014. The couple had their first child, a son named Asher, in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/mlb/diamondbacks/2015/08/15/trades-movement-hard-baseball-families/31752593/|title=Trades, movement hard on baseball families|work=azcentral|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>

